CLINICAL HISTORY: 71 year old woman with epilepsy, admitting with recurrent seizures and sedation.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, Keppra, Lamictal

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is relatively somnolent. Photic simulation is performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a somewhat disorganized pattern. The patient is actually drowsy for much of the record and drifts in and out of stage II sleep. There is a bit of irregular slowing, asymmetric spindles in stage II sleep, more prominent on the left, and occasional right temporal sharp waves. Brief arousals are noted. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is still somewhat sleepy, and there is primarily muscle artifact rather than driving.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background disorganization.
2. Right temporal sharp wave.
3. Beta asymmetry and occasional focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been previously described. No seizures were recorded. The background slowing may represent a postictal state.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old woman with epilepsy, seizures characterized by
ringing in the right ear, dizziness, and woke up with tonic-clonic activity.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Diovan, Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with 10-point 3 Hz alpha rhythm. There is a small amount of wicket activity.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing. Hyperventilation
does not clearly activate the record. There are 2 epileptiform discharges noted in this
record. These include a single well-defined right anterotemporal sharp wave just prior to
photic stimulation and another more subtle during photic. Photic stimulation also elicits
scant driving response.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A single well-defined right anterotemporal sharp wave with another more
equivocal discharge.
CLINICAL The findings described above can be seen in a
localization-related epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  71  year old right handed woman with cognitive problems and episodes of hypotension.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Insulin, Metformin, Prandin, Labetalol, Protonix, Zocor, Reglan
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic simulation was completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, but well organized with 9  Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of blow voltage fronto-central beta activity. Occasional mixed theta and delta is observed
in the temporal regions, right greater than left. Features of drowsiness include slow­
rolling eye movements.   Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 	78  bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is just outside of the range of normal for a subject of this age due to somewhat more than expected temporal slowing from the right. A subject of this age is permitted a small amount of temporal slowing; however, there is a bit more observed from the right than the left and some of it  occurs with a bit more of a sustained beat of 4 Hz pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features noted. The temporal changes described above are nonspecific and can be seen in cerebrovascular disease.
·If additional events occur, additional EEG monitoring in search of epileptiform activity may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old male, status post a complicated aneurysm surgery at age 55,
seizure-free for at least one month but known to have had complicated aneurysm surgery with
ventriculostomy and then another decompressive surgery.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Namenda
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Multiple craniotomy scars are noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized
with shifting arrhythmic delta activity. There is a suggestion at some point of a little bit more
rhythmic slowing on the left and the right and there are rare right temporal sharp waves, some
of which suggest a breach pathology. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. Features
of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.
HR: N/A
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. Shifting slowing, perhaps a bit more so on the right.
3. Occasional right sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a bi-hemispheric disturbance of cerebral
function. The sharp waves are on the right although the patient has a more significant
craniotomy defect on the left. Correlation with imaging is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 68 year old right handed woman with complex partial epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Ability, Alendronate, Advair, Singulair, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is slightly slow with an 8Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There are a handful of suspicious sharp waves which resemble wicket on the left. In addition there is a subtle asymmetry with slightly slower activity on the left compared to the right.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild generalized slowing.
2. Slightly slower pattern on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Well defined epileptiform was not identified,
although there was 1 suspicious sharp wave. Additional EEG either with
sleep deprivation or more prolonged sleep may be helpful to sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old right handed woman with refractory epilepsy, last seizure 2
weeks ago, with 3-4 seizures a month.

MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Tegretol.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 9.5 Hz microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage. frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of rhythmic theta and delta from the left temporal region. In addition, suspicious T1 sharp waves emerge following hyperventilation as the patient becomes drowsy. Later on In the record, there is some beta   frequency artifact picked up In the frontal regions. There is also recurrent, sharply contoured periodic delta picked up at F8. This emerges gradually at 9:04. It does not exactly evolve but it does end abruptly at 9:04:52. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Sharply contoured periodic delta in the right anterior temporal region of approximately 52 seconds duration.
2. Occasional left temporal rhythmic slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. These findings may be correlated with imaging for this individual with what appears to be temporal lobe epilepsy. The left temporal rhythmic slowing has been identified in a previous EEG October 27, 2009.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 24 year old female with new-onset seizures July 2009, history of
developmental delay, bipolar disease, and seizures in infancy.

MEDICATIONS: Cymbalta, Albuterol, Midodrine, Ativan

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is 10.5 Hz 40 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm. There is a small amount of excess beta and a small amount.
of excess theta for an adult of this age. Hyperventilation produces an increase in
amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving. Drowsiness is
characterized by an increase in beta.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess beta .
2. Mild excess theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in a
diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may include this patient's medications.
No epileptiform features were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old male status post massive intracerebral hemorrhage on the 10th, now with fixed and dilated pupils for 24 hours.
MEDICATIONS: Midazolam, Folate, Pantoprazole, Labetalol, Nicardipine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates EKG and other extracerebral artifacts. There is twitch artifact. Stimulation of the patient does not impact the record. No reactivity or variability is identified. This EEG is also recorded in the ECS montage. There are some technical issues in the initial portion of the record which produce artifact, but once these are resolved, the overall recording is of good quality.
HR: 130 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Absence of cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In the appropriate clinical context, this EEG is compatible with electrocerebral inactivity. After the electrode issues were resolved, there is more than 47 minutes of good quality recording which does not demonstrate cerebral activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed woman with a learning disability and
recurrent seizures in sleep with incontinence, tongue biting, and migraine headaches.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is a bit slow,
slightly disorganized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 6-7 Hz, 50 mcv. Features of
drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an
increase in slowing of the background. At the close of the record just before photic,
there are portions of the record are well organized and within normal limits. Photic
stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent, excess theta in wakefulness.
2. Intermittent disorganization for age and wakefulness.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is one of many EEGs including a long-term monitor
for this patient. No seizures have ever been captured, and no epileptiform activity has
been seen. Additional recording in sleep would be necessary to identify epileptiform
activity or seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 69 year old female with dementia with mental status changes.
MEDICATIONS: Insulin, Lovenox, Plavix, Metoprolol, ASA, Rifaximin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a slow and disorganized pattern. The overall pattern is a mixture of delta and theta frequency activity. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle artifact.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slow and disorganized background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. The prominent rhythmicity of the background particularly at the end when the theta frequency activity increases more toward a 6 Hz pattern which is compatible with a chronic dementing illness, but, again, the findings are nonspecific.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old male with left-sided seizures on 2/27/2010, status post 1 mg  Ativan. Past medical history of seizures, stroke and confusion, chronic pain, substance and alcohol abuse. Recurrent hospitalizations for prolonged postictal state.

MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, Keppra, Enalapril, Lovenox, Tylenol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is quite somnolent: Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing beings, the overall pattern is relatively low voltage with a low voltage theta delta pattern. Stimulation of the patient produces a brief alerting but also a fair amount of muscle artifact. The patient drifts in and out of stage II sleep. There are a handful of bursts of sharp waves rare and slowing from the left mid temporal region and a single well defined left anterior temporal sharp wave.

HR: 68 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Low voltage slow background.
2. Generalized background slowing.
3. Rare left temporal sharp wave.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The left temporal sharp waves have been previously described and were much more prominent in the previous EEGs dating back to 2004. This is a lower voltage and slower pattern than many of the studies and that may be part of the postictal state,
medications used to treat status epilepticus or other clinical factors.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old male who had a traumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage with associated infarct while intoxicated. This was followed by a seizure on an unknown date.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is a technically difficult EEG due to the patient's matted hair style as well as his hard collar.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG with the patient resting quietly includes a medium amplitude mixed frequency pattern with primarily theta and smaller amounts of delta. Stimulation of the patient produces eye opening, muscle artifact and a brief glimpse of an alpha rhythm. As he drifts off to sleep, there are features of vertex waves and some bursts of shifting, frontal delta.

HR: 56-90 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Disorganization.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Please consider a followup study following discharge to further evaluate the potential underlying epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 77 year old woman status post code February 25, 2010, now
with facial twitching. Past history of dementia and other multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Lexapro, Glipizide, Lexapro, Enalapril, Simvastatin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a low voltage
theta pattern. The record is Intermittently discontinuous. The patient has intermittent
turning of the head and this is associated with a small amount of myoclonus. The
pattern is more of a generalized pattern, but it does seem to localize to the parietal
region, right greater than left. Stimulation of the patient seems to increase the
myoclonus.
HR: 80-100 bpm and Irregular
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Burst suppression pattern.
2. Absence of clear very active to stimulation aside from stimulus induced myoclonus.
3. Myoclonus associated with focal epileptiform activity in the parietal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings carry a worrisome prognosis in the context
of anoxia. The pattern is not as vigorous as last week raising concerns for significant
CNS pathology. Additional prognostic studies may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old gentleman status post prolonged cardiac arrest on the 14th.

MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin, Plavix, Lasix, Zosyn, ASA, Pravachol, Simvastatin, Pantoprazole, Plavix

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and comatose.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with continuous, frontally predominant bilateral periodic complex. Most of this activity is bilateral and in the frontal regions. There is some variability in the record and on occasion it is a little bit more posterior. The activity waxes and wanes and it clearly demonstrates frequency evolution. Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.

HR: 140 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A PLEDS pattern .with frequency evolution.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This pattern is a worrisome prognostic pattern following cardiac arrest but it is a more epileptiform periodic pattern which may warrant follow-up.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old gentleman status post prolonged cardiac arrest on the 14th.

MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin, Plavix, Lasix, Zosyn, ASA, Pravachol, Simvastatin, Pantoprazole, Plavix

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and comatose.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with continuous, frontally predominant bilateral periodic complex. Most of this activity is bilateral and in the frontal regions. There is some variability in the record and on occasion it is a little bit more posterior. The activity waxes and wanes and it clearly demonstrates frequency evolution. Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.

HR: 140 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A PLEDS pattern with frequency evolution.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This pattern is a worrisome prognostic pattern following cardiac arrest but it is a more epileptiform periodic pattern which may warrant follow-up.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed male with epilepsy with tonic-clonic activity, postictal confusion.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was declined by the patient, but photic stimulation was concluded.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In relaxed wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is a small amount of background theta. As the patient drifts into sleep, there is an increase in background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Very minimally abnormal EEG to due to:
I. Mild excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were performed. This EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 76 year old left handed woman with an aneurysm repair 12 years ago and a syncopal spell in the past year.

MEDICATIONS: Aricept, Fosamax, Labetalol, Namenda

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized. There is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving. On rare occasions, in wakefulness, a breech rhythm is identified in the left temporal region and there are bursts of theta frequency activity with mixed theta delta, more prominent on the left than the right.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Bursts of bilateral theta, left greater than right.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are noted. Compared to other studies, this EEG actually has an improved background, but EEGs have not been performed for for several years.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old male with severe traumatic head injury.
MEDICATIONS: Propofol, Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was performed at bedside using
standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is
intubated and comatose. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a continuous
mixed frequency slow pattern. Occasional sharp waves are observed most of which are
at C3 but with some variability in terms of spread to the left frontocentral or
centrotemporal region. Shifting asymmetries are noted and in this section of the record
the activity is actually slower on the right at times than the left. Intermittent discontinuity
is observed and there are brief bursts of sharp waves at C3.
HR: 70bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowly.
2. Left central sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were noted in the previous first24 hours of
the record. No seizures were recorded. Correlation with clinical history is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old male with seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized. There is excess 6Hz background activity with an 8Hz alpha rhythm. Superimposed upon this there is a focus of slowing with slow delta identified in the right occipital or posterior quadrant. In addition, there are subtle underlying right central, C4 sharp waves observed. Hyperventilation increases the background slowing. Following hyperventilation the patient becomes drowsy and both the focal slowing from the right hemisphere as well as the generalized slowing are accentuated. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess theta.
2. Slow alpha rhythm.
3. Focal slowing from the right posterior quadrant.
4. Right central sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Supportive of focal mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 79 year old right handed woman with a fall, subsequently developing subdural hematoma on 4/19/2010, with a seizure on presentation.

MEDICATIONS: Versed, Fentanyl, Succinylcholine, Dilantin, Insulin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has scalp laceration which impacts electrode placement. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a rhythmic mixture of theta and delta. There is a subtle asymmetry best identified in the right central parietal region with attenuation of activity in that region. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity.

HR: 110 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic background slowing.
2. A more subtle, superimposed asymmetry with lower voltage and slightly slower activity in the right central region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The focal features described above are quite subtle and, in fact, comparing the central regions bilaterally, the central regions are slower than the temporal regions. This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old male with right frontal ICH.

MEDICATIONS: Phenobarb, Dilantin, Ativan, Keppra, Valium, Vecuronium,
Vancomycin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient has a trach and is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG initially demonstrates a very low voltage suppressed pattern. Superimposed upon this, are-sharp waves in the right hemisphere which typically start in the right posterior quadrant and end in the right anterior region. They seem to occur as a couplet and with posterior sharp waves first and then an anterior sharp wave which follows and can occur up to a second later. In some cases, this seems to occur a second and a half later, but the epileptiform activity typically seems to occur with 2-3 discharges at a time. Over the course of the record, there is an improvement in the background with an increase in beta and alpha frequency activity. The epileptiform activity remains relatively in variant.

IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Periodic complexes in the right hemisphere with complex epileptiform activity with unusual localization starting in the posterior region and then ending over a long duration of time to the anterior region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as an epileptogenic process on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old male with a history of head trauma. Rare early morning seizures typically associated with exhaustion and missing medications.

MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient reports he has not had a seizure since March.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and produces sustained, rhythmic right frontotemporal 2-3 Hertz activity. Following this, as the patient drifts into sleep there are rare right anterior temporal sharp waves noted. The patient is awakened from sleep for photic stimulation which elicits a generally bilateral driving response which is relatively subtle but there is also rhythmic slowing and a handful of sharp waves noted during photic stimulation.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region.
2. Rare right anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. Epileptiform activity was more prominent in the EEG in comparison to previous studies including a normal1-hour study in 2007 and an abnormal study in 2006.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old woman admitted 2 days ago status post severe
head trauma with cerebral edema.

MEDICATIONS: Vasopressin, Epinephrine, Dopamine, Phenylephrine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and
comatose.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is examined during the EEG. The EEG
is an electronic format. Sections of the record are performed with the ECS montage.
There is no definitive cerebral activity. There is EKG and other artifacts, including some
rhythmic artifacts picked up at 02. Stimulation of the patient does not activate the
record. There is no variability. The electrode integrity is tested by the technologist.

HR: 120 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Electrocerebral inactivity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: In the appropriate clinical context, in the absence of
profound hypothermia or medications which might explain this pattern, this EEG is
compatible with electrocerebral silence.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old right handed male with epilepsy. Left.sided stroke
with encephalomalacia and now bilateral strokes.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10·20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has received 5 mg
Ativan and is quite somnolent. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a very slow
pattern, low voltage with delta and smaller amounts of beta. There is intermittent
background attenuation. There are a handful of low voltage, right frontotemporal sharp
waves as well as rare sharp waves noted on the left which can be differentiated from
EKG and other artifacts. The patient's transitioning into stage II sleep during photic
stimulation which does not otherwise activate the record.
HR: 90bpm .
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background with low voltage slow pattern.
2. A handful of proudly contoured sharp waves in the right anterior temporal or
frontocentral region.
3. Rare left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This-record is significantly slower and lower voltage than
previous studies. In the 2 previous studies available for comparison, the epileptiform
activity was higher amplitude and more easily defined on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old male with subdural hematomas, hepatitis C, recurrent
craniotomies, complex partial seizures February 15, 2010 following craniotomy with seizures out of the left central temporal region. None reported since then.

MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital, Senna, Acetaminophen

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed. The patient has a tracheostomy and is on supplemental oxygen and is poorly
responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a medium to low
voltage pattern. The right hemisphere includes primarily a 6 Hz rhythmic background with a
smaller amount of alpha frequency activity and a suggestion of a theta frequency, posterior dominant rhythm. The activity from the left hemisphere is lower voltage, slower, although the posterior dominant rhythm is, on occasion, identified. Brief arousals in the record are associated with an increase in alpha frequency activity, right greater than left. There is occasional frontal delta left greater than right. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, right greater than left. Heart rate 84 BPM. At the close of the record, asymmetric eye movement artifact is identified, again primarily in the left frontal region. There is a combination of eye artifact higher amplitude on the
left than the right and some left frontocentral slowing with occasional C3 sharp waves.

HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Interhemispheric asymmetry with lower voltage, slower activity on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The generalized slowing and the focal slowing have been
previously described and support a bihemispheric process as well as a focal, structural process on the left involving gray and white matter. Epileptiform activity was markedly reduced today compared to previous studies. No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old right handed male with episodes of loss of
consciousness which improve with the use of Dilantin. The patient, however, denies the
history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is
somewhat slow with an alpha rhythm typically at 7 Hz to 8 Hz. There is a smaller
amount of faster 10 and 11 Hz frequency activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on
in the record producing an increase in amplitude of the background. Vertex waves are
identified in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits no driving response.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. This is both a
diffusely slow record and a drowsy individual. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a
repeat study may be considered.

CLINICAL 38 year old right handed gentleman with encephalopathy admitted with refractory seizures, worsening aphagia, right foot numbness and worsening right hemiparesis, occasional myoclonus.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate, Steroids, Dilantin, Klonopin, Lisinopril, Prednisone, Protonix, Coumadin, Lipitor
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a significantly slow pattern on the right with lower voltage, mixed theta delta pattern. The left hemisphere demonstrates arrhythmic delta activity with high amplitude epileptiform activity with complex field of spread including posterior temporal. Some of the epileptiform activity is at the vertex. Much of it appears at PZ or T5. There is an electropositivity at CZ that marches through in the averaged reference with an electronegativity P3T5. In addition, there are other wave forms that are actually electronegative and maximum at PZCA compatible with very complex epileptiform activity. The highest amplitude activity is a left posterior temporal spike focus. The epileptiform activity occurs. as frequent but relatively isolated discharges which do not evolve, although the activity at CZPZ does seem to have more of a rhythmic pattern. Photic stimulation does not appreciably change the EEG.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex epileptiform activity in the left hemisphere with an unusual field of spread.
2. Epileptiform activity at CZPZ.
3. Arrhythmic delta on the left.
4. More rhythmic lower voltage slowing on the right.  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function but more importantly a focal mechanism for seizures. Although there was prominent epileptiform activity, no sustained or evolving ictal discharges were observed.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

There is occasional, slightly irregular slowing in the temporal regions, notched, 5 Hz activity is noted in the frontal region which is typically symmetric and bilateral. Features of drowsiness could an increase in background stowing. Vertex waves are identified in stage I sleep. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing bursts of rhythmic frontal activity which is somewhat sharply contoured. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rare, right frontal sharp waves.
2. Shifting slowing.
3. Small degree of background disorganization.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old male with new onset seizures.

Although not all of the seizures have a clear clinical correlate and some have only either subtle theta or subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in the left temporal region, some have clear, rhythmic 4 hertz theta from the left temporal region with some spread to the frontocentral region bilaterally, typically lasting 20-40 seconds. The patient receives Depakote at 2:20 p.m., the discharges are briefer, more evanescent more allusive.
Event time 12930: the patient has a dizzy spell characterized by decreased alpha frequency activity from the left temporal region and a brief burst of left temporal theta.
Event time: 2:32 p.m.: There is a brief burst of left temporal theta which differs from the background.
Event time: 3:12p.m.: Aura of dizziness, left temporal theta.
Event #3: Aura characterized by dizziness time 335 to 33729, rhythmic temporal theta as described above.
Event #4: Subtle left temporal theta at 3:53:52.
Event #5: 536, very subtle left temporal theta.
Event #6: Aura 5:46:13, brief burst of left temporal theta.
HR: 100 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region.
2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread.
3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with recurrent status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Solu-Medrol, Lacosamide, Topamax, Benzodiazepines, Klonopin, Zocor, Lovenox, Protonix
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is drowsy. DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG even before the patient begins to have seizures is markedly abnormal. The right hemisphere is slow with a theta frequency pattern and the left hemisphere has a higher amplitude sharply contoured delta in the context of a breach rhythm. The left TS sharp waves are noted. The TS sharp waves start to build up into a train and as they do, fast activity is noted particularly in the central regions Cz/C3 and then with some transmission to the contralateral side. Using alternative montages, the activity seems to generate from TS to a Cv/C3 focus. The activity can also be reviewed with average reference and seems to emanate from TS to a CZ more than C3 focus, building up along the midline with 13 Hz activity which gradually slows and the seizure seems to end in the left central parietal region with a spiking at CZ rather than P3 or TS. In the postictal section, the background is slow and then additional seizures build up again with this bursts of 13 Hz activity in the left central and midline region. The patient is uncomfortable during the seizures. In addition, he is drowsy but is somewhat responsive. He experiences uncomfortable focal motor activity and confusion and staring. Multiple brief seizures occur during the EEG.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Status epilepticus pattern with recurrent seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a focal mechanism for seizures. The fast activity at the midline is a relatively new pattern for this individual.

Generalized slow waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  69 year old with history of metastatic disease, adenocarcinoma with brain metastasis, hydrocephalus status post shunt, hypertension and parietal craniotomy, who presents with change in mental status.

Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs) seen at T3, at times with a more posterior field at T5 and more central field at C3 with a frequency of 0.5-1 Hz and an amplitude of 20-100 microvolts.
Focal slow waves seen in the left hemisphere, maximal at T3 with associated loss of faster frequencies over that hemisphere.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left mid temporal PLEDs with a large field over the left posterior quadrant.
Focal slow waves and lack of faster frequencies over that region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed 18-weeks' pregnant with first-ever seizures, family history of epilepsy, aneurysm and eclampsia.

There is a single paroxysmal burst noted in that transition which is generalized, but is suspicious for a discharge on the left.  As she is falling asleep during photic stimulation, there are a handful of bursts with isolated paroxysmal 5 Hz activity, but not definitive spike and wave activity.  The individual appears to be excessively sleepy.  Limited wakefulness is achieved.

2 subtle bursts of 5 Hz activity not exactly during photic stimulation, but around the time of photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG did not adequately identify epileptiform activity.  There are, of course, constraints in the evaluation of a pregnant patient.  The features

CLINICAL HISTORY:  41 year old right handed male with Rasmussen’s encephalitis with increasing seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, Lacosamide, Phenobarbital, Klonopin, Lipitor, Pantoprazole, Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  As the record begins, the activity includes a prominent interhemispheric asymmetry.  It is medium amplitude, but slow, primarily theta on the right with some occasional posterior delta.  From there left there is clearly a breach with a high amplitude spike and slow-wave complex at T3 and T5.  It is also picked up at C3/P3.
The first seizure occurs within 1 minute with a burst of 14 Hz activity emanating from the left frontal region with frequency evolution.  This is over 4 minutes and 35 seconds into the EEG.  Additional seizure occurs at 4 minutes and 40 seconds, and another similar seizure with the fast activity from the left frontal region at 3 Hz photic stimulation.  In that seizure, focal spiking is noted at T5.  Photic stimulation does not otherwise activate the record.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing to the left hemisphere with disruption of faster frequency activity.
Modest slowing from the right.
Epileptiform activity in the left hemisphere which may be centrotemporal, left hemispheric, or left posterior temple.
Unusual seizure pattern which seems to start with 14 Hz activity from the frontal and frontotemporal regions on the left but ends with a posterior temporal spike.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is not substantially different from previous EEG monitoring sessions for this individual, although these seizures are exquisitely focal.  Additional EEG monitoring will be initiated as pharmacotherapy is implemented.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old man, found unresponsive with a temperature of 95.7 with a history of substance abuse, asthma, now found to have a right cerebral intraparenchymal hemorrhage with intraventricular extension and an EVD placed.  Now with left gaze deviation.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video  EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient was lethargic during the examination.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow, low amplitude background with an asymmetric hemisphere amplitude and frequency.  Over the right hemisphere, there appears to be marked attenuation and lack of faster frequencies with some focal F8/T4 slowing.  Over the left hemisphere, there appears to be diffuse slowing, however, while the patient is stimulated, there appeared to be an increase of the faster frequencies and some reactivity.  No normal frontocentral beta is seen.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No photic stimulation or hyperventilation was performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Right hemispheric attenuation and slowing maximal at F8/T4 with no reactivity to pain.
Generalized slowing with some reactivity seen maximal at the left hemisphere.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemispheric slowing maximal in the right anterior temporal region with associated loss of faster frequencies and decreased.
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structure dysfunction and cortical damage over the right hemisphere seen maximally in the temporal region, which may be related at least in part to the hemorrhage.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed male with family history of epilepsy, with 2 tonic-clonic seizure in association with generous alcohol ingestion.

In relaxed wakefulness, there are brief bursts of 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing bursts of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity, some of which are isolated, some of which are associated with frontal delta.  These are present bilaterally, but with a somewhat more generous field of spread posteriorly on the left.  Hyperventilation produces the bursts of spike and wave activity, but which seemed to be associated with a little jerking of the leg, but which were all less than 1 second in duration and were not associated with impairment of awareness.  As he drifts off to sleep, there is an increase in beta and some faster spike and wave complexes occurring as couplets.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Photic driving is noted at low frequency stimuli and immediately after photic is completed, spike and wave activity is observed.  There is some head rocking or single-channel electrode at P3 at the end of the EEG.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 3-5.5 Hz spike and wave activity noted in relaxed wakefulness and accentuated by hyperventilation, but no photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most compatible with inherited or familial mechanism for seizures.

Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  However, during hyperventilation the patient does start complaining of left arm numbness and pain.  During this time and intermittently there appears to be a change in the EKG lead to what appears to be bigeminy for seconds intermittently.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal attenuation of the entire right hemisphere and disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm seen throughout the recording.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness, along with bursts of FIRDA in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  During the recording the patient complained of her left arm hurting, which is consistent with her typical events, but there is no EEG correlate during this event.  The patient did not loose consciousness.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere attenuation and disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm in that hemisphere.
Mild generalized slowing.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cortical dysfunction in the right hemisphere, which is consistent with a known hemiatrophy seen on the right hemisphere for this patient.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The episodes of left arm burning did not have any EEG correlate.  However, please note that up to 75% of simple partial seizures may not be captured during scalp EEG.  Lastly, the patient did have some EKG abnormalities seen throughout the recording.  Due to this the patient was recommended to be seen in the emergency room right after the EEG.  She was taken there for this.

Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
Right hemisphere attenuation of faster frequencies.

Generalized slowing as well as right hemisphere attenuation and left mid-temporal slowing.

In addition, there is evidence of mild focal structural dysfunction in the right hemisphere which may be consistent with the previous strokes.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  79 year old right handed woman with a left MCA stroke, right-sided weakness, and hypertension.  Admitted with seizure characterized by right gaze deviation.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the awake EEG demonstrates asymmetry.  There is a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm on the right which is disrupted on the left.  The faster frequency activity is disrupted on the left in the left temporal region relative to the right.  In addition, there is somewhat periodic arrhythmic delta activity with a complex field of spread in the left temporal region.  It may start left mid temporal or posterior temporal and then spread to the left hemisphere, particularly centrotemporal regions or the left posterior temporal area.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are some bursts of frontal delta bilaterally.  Other features of drowsiness include an accentuation of the left temporal focal slowing. Rare left temporal sharp waves maximum at T1-T3 are observed.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.  Heart rate 104 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A slightly slow and disorganized record on the right.
Arrhythmic delta in the left hemisphere with some poorly formed periodic complexes in the left.
Rare left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional process on the left, involving gray and white matter.  These sharp waves are congruent with the prior left MCA infarct.  This EEG is similar to 2 prior EEGs for this patient.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  57 year old right handed male with adult-onset epilepsy, last seizure 1 month ago.  The patient has a 2-day aura of déjà vu before he has a seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Enalapril, Lipitor
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.

In relaxed wakefulness and in hyperventilation, there is rhythmic 3-5 Hz activity in the right temporal region.  Some of this occurs in bursts, but without definitive frequency evolution.  The bursts of rhythmic temporal theta delta may be associated with right temporal sharp waves.  In hyperventilation, the alpha rhythm is also disrupted relative to the alpha on the contralateral side.  Features of drowsiness include accentuation of the right temporal slowing and sharp waves.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response a little bit more vigorous on the left than the right.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent rhythmic right temporal focal slowing.
Right anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Features described above are characteristic of temporal lobe epilepsy.  No seizures were recorded, although this was a very rhythmic and irritative process.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed male with a history of febrile convulsions.  The patient had a concussion and developed more seizures, and required a vagal nerve stimulator.  In April he had several tonoclonic seizures with loss of consciousness and aura.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG includes a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient transitions in and out of sleep with prominent, hypnagogic hypersynchrony.  During photic stimulation, however, 6 Hz spike and wave activity is noted.  This is noted again during photic stimulation with a 5.5 Hz very brief spike and wave complex during various different photic stimulation parameters. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the frontally predominant relatively symmetric spike and wave activity. On at least 1 occasion during the EEG, neuro artifact is noted, but no definitive vagal nerve stimulator artifact was observed.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 5.5 Hz spike and wave activity accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is a normal phenomenon, but may resemble a forme-fruste of the generalized spike and wave activity.  This patient clearly had generalized spike and wave activity.  This is more supportive of a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  In this particular EEG, there were no asymmetries and there is otherwise a normal background.

The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild excessive theta of 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-50 microvolts in wakefulness.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  41 year old right handed woman with alcohol abuse, hepatitis, cirrhosis, bacteremia, hepatic encephalopathy, delirium and asterixis.
MEDICATIONS:  Actigall, Pentoxifylline, Unasyn, Hydrocortisone, Betamethasone, Thiamine, Folic Acid, Rifaximin, Protonix, Propranolol, Prednisone
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Although the patient did not seem to be moving around very much in the EEG, she was described by the technologist as quite tense and there was a great deal of muscle artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is slow and disorganized with diffuse theta.  There is a glimpse of a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There are posteriorly predominant bilateral triphasic waves noted which are ameliorated by tactile stimulation.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Disorganization.
Posteriorly predominant triphasic waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Triphasic waves are hallmarks of a metabolic encephalopathy and are usually anteriorly maximum.  No seizures were seen.  The patient's tremulousness was associated with an increase in muscle artifact.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old right handed woman with stroke, encephalomalacia, pacemaker.  The patient now has episodes where she stares into space, cannot interact, and does not recall what happened.  Evaluate for complex partial epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is low voltage.  There is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified.  The patient seems to be drowsy during much of the EEG and in that transition to drowsiness, focal slowing was noted in the right hemisphere with a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in the right hemisphere, particularly the temporal region.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by vertex waves.  Stage II sleep is overall symmetric. Photic stimulation elicited scant bilateral driving.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle focal slowing characterized by transition focal features on the right with drop out of the alpha rhythm on the right before the left.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  45 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old woman admitted on 09/27/2012, for altered mental status, rapid response code on 09/28/2012, for change in mental status.  This EEG is being performed to assess for a stroke versus seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, venlafaxine, Protonix, vancomycin, folic acid, thiamine, Zosyn, and Serax.  An additional 2 mg of Ativan was given during the recording for muscle artifact.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background is symmetric and continuous.  The background consists of very low amplitude fast activity without anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient. Nearly continuous EMG artifact is present over the bilateral lateral leads.
With stimulation there is an increase in EMG artifact diffusely, however, there is no discernible change in background.
No normal sleep architecture is captured.
A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate of approximately 120 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:  Diffusely attenuated EEG with primarily beta background.  No clear electrographic seizures.  Nearly continuous EEG artifact over the bilateral lateral leads.  Tachycardia.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 45-minute EEG due to diffusely low voltages and diffuse beta activity without clear normal organizations.  These findings indicate nonspecific cerebral dysfunction that in this case could partially be related to medication effect.  There is nearly continuous muscle artifact over the bilateral lateral leads that
limits interpretation of the recording.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.  Sinus tachycardia is observed in a single EKG lead.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 43-year-old male with schizophrenia and 20 year history of epilepsy, transferred from Episcopal after 4 tonic clonic seizures with subsequent seizures on route to the hospital.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Dilantin, Depakote, Haldol, clindamycin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was initially comatose.  The patient was intubated throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The initial sections of the record demonstrated a low voltage, slow record with delta and frontal beta.
As the recording continues, tactile stimulation of the patient results in an alerting response with eye opening, lower voltage fast beta pattern and spontaneous movements of all extremities of the patient.  As the recording continues, the patient starts to drift back towards stage II sleep.
Heart rate:  78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to: Replacement of normal background with low voltage and generalized slow pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Brief alerting response identified is a positive finding for this individual with recent status epilepticus.  No epileptiform features were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old, left handed male, with epilepsy as a child, seizure free for 2 years, but recurrent seizures on October 15, 2012 characterized by right shaking for 1-2 minutes with tongue biting, loss of consciousness, and postictal confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with  channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In apparent wakefulness, there is a glimpse of 9 Hz alpha rhythm, but there is excess theta.  Higher amplitude, triangular shaped, frontal delta was noted even prior to hyperventilation.
Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the high amplitude theta, as well as the bursts of FIRDA.  Bursts of higher amplitude delta were noted during photic stimulation and after photic stimulation, but without spike and wave activity.  Photic stimulation elicited a driving response at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
Heart rate:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Excess theta.
It seems to be frontally predominant rhythmic mixed theta delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG may hide an underlying frontal epileptiform focus.  A follow up EEG with cognitive testing is advised to more clearly determine when the patient is maximally awake.  In addition, more extended sleep may be helpful in capturing epileptiform activity.  The higher amplitude frontal slowing is not as apparent as the patient transitions into sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 46-year-old female with left posterior temporal AVM and clips brought in with first episode of seizure described as shaking all over with tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS:  Chlorhexidine and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead  EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while confused, unresponsive, and lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 5-7 Hz and there is some frontal central beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:
Frequent T5 sharp waves seen throughout the recording.  At times the sharp waves would suddenly become rhythmic and continue for about 2-3 minutes and then stop.  They did not clearly evolve, but became extremely arrhythmic throughout this time.
Focal slowing seen at T5 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Moderate diffuse slowing at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
Seizures:  As above mentioned there is bursts of T5 sharp waves that did not clearly evolve, but would start and stop suddenly, at times for minutes with no clinical correlate.  These are concerning for possible electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior temporal sharp waves and monomorphic discharges concerning for electrographic seizures, in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left posterior temporal region.  Note:  The bursts of rhythmic sharp waves were concerning for electrographic seizures, as they had no clinical correlate.  In addition, there is evidence of moderate diffuse slowing, which may due at least in part to medication effect.  These findings were reported to the primary team who decided to treat the patient and will place the patient on long term monitoring.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This patient is a 46-year-old female brought in for first episode of seizure described as shaking all over, tongue biting, history of left-sided AVM with clips.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during lethargy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  Activities during the procedure were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen almost continuously and frequently at T5 with a large field that spread over the left hemisphere.
Focal slowing seen continuously over the left hemisphere maximal at T5 and frequency at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  The posterior temporal sharp waves at T5 appear to start and stop but at times appear to evolve in frequency and increase in amplitude and then suddenly stop and start again.  There appears to be no clinical correlation to this burst that may last for minutes but are most consistent with electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to recurring electrographic left posterior temporal seizures, in addition to left posterior temporal focal cerebral dysfunction, which is consistent with the known AVM.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to activity and may be due at least in part due to medication affect.  These findings were reported to the primary team as soon as the EEG was read at 7:00 p.m. on 10/22/2012.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 46-year-old woman with catamenial epilepsy status post right temporal lobectomy, seizure free, follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, zonisamide, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures only included photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Heart rate 60.
The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is frontocentral beta which is slightly high amplitude over the right hemisphere.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  In addition, there is increase of faster frequencies in this region, both consistent with breach rhythm.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 36-year-old woman with epilepsy, anxiety disorder and pancreatitis.  The patient's last seizure was 2 weeks ago.  The seizures begin with an aura followed by tongue biting and incontinence.  The seizures are typically nocturnal.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Creon, cyclobenzaprine, Benadryl, lamotrigine, metoprolol, ondansetron, oxycodone, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of background theta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in slowing, particularly in the central regions and disappearance of the alpha rhythm.  Sleep is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  A mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age in wakeful and limited drowsiness due to:
Mild excess theta.
Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is similar to a previous study this year.  Neither EEG captured stage II sleep.  A repeat study capturing sleep is suggested to more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 46-year-old woman with left parietal AVM, neurofibromatosis, newly diagnosed refractory epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient has reportedly had recently coiling.   Technically, this is a difficult study in a patent who keeps scratching and moving about.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there are sections of the record where there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  The right hemisphere remains a little bit slow and disorganized.  The left hemisphere demonstrates intermittent arrhythmic delta activity with relatively complex sharp waves noted in the left hemisphere including left mid to anterior temporal region as well as sometimes posterior temporal region.  There are also a handful of sharp waves noted in the right central temporal region. The focal slowing on the left may occur as more prolonged paroxysmal bursts or be a little bit more subtle and irregular.  In stage II sleep, vertex waves and spindles were identified.

Background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed left focal slowing.
Sharp waves seen from the left hemisphere with various different localizations including left hemisphere, left temporal but also now on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 77-year-old male with systolic heart failure, tachycardia.  recent C3-C4 posterior cervical laminectomy.  Change in mental status with episodes of tongue movement and eye deviation.
MEDICATIONS:  Acyclovir, Depakote, antibiotics, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient was intubated, but awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of theta and frontocentral beta.  The technologist notes significant ICU artifacts and there is some muscle artifact in the frontal regions.  There are rare shifting asymmetries in the frontal region in terms of faster frequently activity.
Heart rate 126 BPM.

Mild excess beta.
Mild excess theta.
