CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 59-year-old woman with chronic static encephalopathy.  Epilepsy as an infant, followed by a closed head injury at age 5 with a development of refractory epilepsy, now seizure free for many years.
MEDICATIONS:  Diamox, primidone, calcium, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background, the EEG includes a diffusely slow pattern with a 7.5 Hz alpha and a background rich in rhythmic theta.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at faster flash frequencies.  Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is similar to an EEG in 2009.  No epileptiform features were identified in today's EEG.  There is a very small amount of shifting slowing.  This may be an age-related finding.  No epileptiform features were noted in the last 2 EEGs.  In 1990’s, when the patient was having frequent seizures, electrographic seizures were identified from the left temporal region with interictal right temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old gentleman who suffered a cerebral abscess in the 90's, subsequent development of epilepsy with four seizures per month.  He reports seizures began with a feeling of numbness or burning in his feet followed by loss of awareness with tongue biting, incontinence following generalized shaking.  Last seizure two weeks ago.  Seizures have increased with life's stress.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was awake and conversant throughout.  He has a prominent, frontal craniotomy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is an unusual and dynamic EEG.  Some sections of the record demonstrate a pretty well organized background with a lower voltage alpha rhythm of 11 Hz and some lower voltage frontocentral theta.  Other sections of the record demonstrated bursts of high amplitude, bifrontal sharp waves or spikes.  These occur with the patient relaxing comfortably but were accentuated by hyperventilation.  The epileptiform activity is usually bilateral but can be maximum in the right or left frontal region.  There can be a polyspike component at FP1, F3 or FP2.  The bursts of slow spike-and-wave activity are associated with background slowing, and bursts of epileptiform activity or bursts of slowing with epileptiform may be on the order of two seconds or longer.  Aside from these bursts, the patient is awake, alert, and conversant.  The bursts are brief enough that it is difficult to determine if they are clinically significant.
Heart rate:  72  BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Burst of slow, frontal spike-and-wave activity.
Associated focal slowing noted with these bursts.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In the context of this patient's significance neurosurgical history, the location of the epileptiform activity is anticipated.  Despite the bursts of slowing, the patient was relatively asymptomatic.  In this individual with frequent seizures, additional EEG recording may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 74-year-old male, status post severe head trauma, patient discharged to a nursing home and then re-admitted on 11/11/2012.  Evaluate for impaired mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Amantadine, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a pattern of low voltage data, intermittently interrupted by rhythmic 1 to 2 Hz delta activity.  In addition, there is some shifting arrhythmic delta activity, a little bit more prominent on the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in delta.
Heart rate 114 bmp.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
A patient suffering with traumatic brain injury who does demonstrate some alerting but with minimal alerting, a low alpha rhythm.
Bursts of delta.
Mild shifting and slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with both a neurodegenerative process with dementia, such as Parkinson's disease and severe traumatic brain injury.  This EEG demonstrates a slow background.  There was a section where the patient seemed to be awake with tremor and there was an emergence of an alpha rhythm but the patient did not seem to be very interactive at that time.  Clinical management may be the most important tool to follow his mental status.  No epileptiform features were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with a history of seizures; followup for recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Very frequent, at times rhythmic sharp waves seen over F7/T3 and at times at T3 during wakefulness and sleep, as well independent also frequent sharp waves over F8/T4, also seen during wakefulness and sleep; however, the majority of the sharp waves are seen mainly in sleep and appear to attenuate with eye opening and wakefulness.
Focal slow waves over the left hemisphere at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts and independently at F8/T4, seen occasionally at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate 78, regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to very frequent left anterior temporal and independent right anterior temporal sharp waves in wakefulness and sleep, as well as focal slowing in those regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from either anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of independent focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal regions, both of which are nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that this EEG is not that dissimilar to the reported EEG done on August 1, 2011.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG at bedside, awake and sleep.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 33-year-old right-handed woman, with past medical history of diabetes and moyamoya disease status post surgical revascularization who presents with 3 days history of headache and transient slurred speech.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  in the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 11-12 Hz in frequency, 40-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically, stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts.  There are occasional bursts of left anterior and mid temporal slowing at 67/T3 in wakefulness and sleep consisting of 3-3.5 Hz delta frequency, mixed with 4-5 Hz theta activity lasting for 1-2 seconds.  There were no epileptiform discharges or seizures noted during this recording.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to the left temporal slowing seen during wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of a structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction in this case secondary to history of left MCA stroke.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  If seizure activity is a clinical concern, a bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with alcohol abuse, admitted with change in mental status, right arm tremor, and eye deviation to the left; evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a fair amount of muscle and movement artifact.  There is a mixed frequency pattern with generous faster frequency activity and some slow activity with a mixture of theta/delta.  There is a great deal of chew artifact noted.  Shifting asymmetries were observed.  Very brief epochs to suggest stage I sleep were noted, followed immediately by spontaneous agitation.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Prominent shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Sleep was not sustained.  There is shifting slowing in the sleep morphologies as well as in the overall background.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  No epileptiform features were identified, but a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy should be considered.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 32-year-old man with history of seizures after a motor vehicle accident in 1995.  Last seizure 1-2 months ago with staring spells and shaking.  Denies loss of consciousness.  Lasted 5-10 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote and Zonegran.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is a lack of normal frontal central beta.  Overall, the background has intermittent generalized slowing, even during wakefulness in the theta range, which is intermixed with a frontal predominant delta slowing seen in the bilateral frontal regions.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness, and activating procedures were performed including hyperventilation and photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There was continuous frontalis and temporalis muscle artifact seen continuously throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen in the bilateral frontal regions with a low amplitude and a frequency of 2-4 Hz.
Generalized slow waves.  There is excessive theta in wakefulness at 5-7 Hz seen frequently throughout the recording.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  60
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral frontal slowing as well as mild excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral frontal region, in addition to mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, of which may be related to his previous injury, although they are nonspecific findings.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  Approximately 22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 61-year-old man with right basal ganglia hemorrhage.  He now has a change in mental status.  EEG is being performed to rule out subclinical seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During wakefulness, the background consists of a mixture of low to moderate amplitude, at times sharply contoured theta and delta activity with under-riding faster frequencies, as well as some occasional waveforms of triphasic morphology.  During sleep, background voltage decreases and the background consists of a mixture of theta and delta activity that is better organized.  Additional nearly continuous polymorphic delta activity is observed over the right hemisphere and is mostly pronounced over the frontotemporal regions.  There are occasional variable amplitude sharp waves with  aftergoing slow waves observed over the right occipital region, right midtemporal region, and right centroparietal region.  Occasionally, the discharges over the right central temporoparietal region are synchronized.  Once asleep, frequency of the discharges improves and they are only rarely observed over the right midtemporal region.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not observed.  There were no clear electrographic seizures.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing and disorganization.
Multifocal sharp waves over the right hemisphere, observed over the occipital region, midtemporal region, and centroparietal region.
EEG shows normalization during sleep.
No electrographic seizures.S
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal awake and asleep 22-minute electroencephalogram due to moderate diffuse slowing, disorganization, and the multifocal sharp waves observed over the right hemisphere, and focal right hemispheric slowing most pronounced over the right frontotemporal region.  Diffuse slowing and disorganization indicate moderate degree of cerebral dysfunction that is etiologically nonspecific.  Focal right hemispheric slowing indicates underlying focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology and is consistent with patient's history of right basal ganglia hemorrhage.  Multifocal sharp waves over the right hemisphere indicate increased epileptogenic potential, however, since they improve during sleep they are more likely to be related to toxic metabolic disturbance.  There are no clear electrographic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 47-year-old right-handed male with a history of seizures, hypertension, and schizophrenia.  This is a followup study.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Depakote, Ativan, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  He is awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background demonstrates a slow posterior dominant rhythm at 7-8 Hz with a smaller amount of background theta.  The patient appears to be quite sleepy and drifting off.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of eye blink artifact and muscle artifact and appearance of posts and vertex sharp transients.  The patient reaches a stage II sleep and fluctuates in and out.  Photic stimulation reveals driving response.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of background activity.  There were no epileptiform discharges or seizures during this recording.  Heart rate 70-80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings are consistent with mild encephalopathy that can be caused by toxic metabolic degenerative infectious etiologies.  This pattern was seen in his previous EEGs.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures were identified during this recording.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  The absence of epileptiform discharges does not exclude epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 31-year-old woman with epilepsy, seizure free for 15 years but with recurrent seizures 6 months ago.  The patient also had a recent seizure 6 days ago described as eyes rolling up with generalized shaking for 10 minutes and incontinence with tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is an unusual background.  Some sections of the record in wakefulness are well organized.  There is a 10 Hertz alpha rhythm.  In wakefulness there is intermittent, rhythmic, 4-6 Hertz theta activity.  In addition, there is irregular, left temporal theta as well as some rhythmic left temporal theta with sharp wave or sharply contoured slowing typically maximum at T3, occasionally T1.  Focal features were also noted from the right with occasional bursts of slowing on the right.  There is EKG artifacts but the sharply contoured slowing is more prominent on the left.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.  Heart 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Left temporal focal slowing.
Intermittent generalized slowing.
Independent, rhythmic slowing from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates a bi-hemispheric disturbance.  The mechanism for this patient's epilepsy, however, may be in the left temporal region.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 73-year-old man who presents with new onset of loss of consciousness on 12/27/2012 that lasted less than 15 seconds with return to baseline.  Prior to the event the patient felt a warm sensation rising to his head.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During very brief arousal there is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no clear anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background during very brief arousal consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta activity mixed with under-riding faster frequencies.  There is excess beta seen diffusely.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in no additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
Primarily asleep study
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal minimally awake, mostly asleep, 22-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, however, it could also represent excessively drowsy patient.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 55-year-old man with a history of aneurysmal surgery, left frontal stroke, hemiparesis, and seizures.  EEG is being performed to assess the patient's baseline.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include phenobarbital, Dilantin, Prozac, and others.
CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10/20 system, with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is continuous right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster waveforms over the left hemisphere.  Of note, the patient is asleep throughout most of the recording.  During brief wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm over the left consists of moderate amplitude 9-10 Hz alpha activity. PGR No comment can be made about reactivity.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere.  Additionally, continuous excess beta activity is captured over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere is not clearly visualized.  The background during maximal wakefulness over the right consists of a mixture of polymorphic alpha and theta activity.  Additional polymorphic delta activity with paucity of faster frequencies is observed during drowsiness and sleep over the right hemisphere, primarily over the right frontotemporal region.  Intermittent moderate to high amplitude sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves are captured over the right anterior temporal region.  Phase reversal occurs over F8/T4 electrodes.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in no additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the right frontotemporal region.
Excess beta activity observed over the left hemisphere.
Suspected breach artifact over the left hemisphere.
Intermittent sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves over the right anterior temporal region, with phase reversal over F8/T4 electrodes.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal, mostly asleep, very briefly awake EEG due to continuous focal right hemispheric slowing, that is most pronounced over the right frontotemporal region, and intermittent epileptiform discharges over the right anterior temporal region.  These findings indicate likely underlying focal cerebral dysfunction that carries increased epileptogenic potential.  Excess beta observed over the left hemisphere could be secondary to the medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates. Breach effect could be secondary to a skull defect. Breach effect over that region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old male with a past medical history of ruptured aneurysms status post surgery, stroke, and subsequent seizures who has been seizure free for several years. This EEG is a part of an evaluation to stop Dilantin due to liver problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Patient has been on Dilantin, amlodipine, pravastatin, Lasix, metoprolol, and losartan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is slow with the posterior dominant rhythm of 7-8 Hz through a excess theta activity during wakefulness.  Drowsiness was characterized by more slowing of the background activity and loss of absence of eye blink artifact and muscle artifact.  There is right breach rhythm.  There is also almost continuous right temporal slowing with a frequency of 4.5-5 Hz.  There are occasional bursts of left temporal slowing.  There are intermittent spikes noted with maximum voltage at T4 with no evolutions.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing. Diffuse background slowing
Right breach rhythm.
Continuous right temporal slowing.
Occasional left temporal slowing.
Spikes T4(Right Temporal) occasionally with no evolution, or seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATIONS:  Diffuse slowing is indicative of bihemispheric dysfunctions that could be due to infectious, degenerative, hypoxic ischemic, postictal, and toxic metabolic etiologies. Clinical correlation is recommended.  Right breach rhythm could be due to the history of craniotomy in the past. Continuous right temporal slowing could be due to structural lesions in the right temporal region.  The presence of spike in right temporal region is indicative of hyperexcitability of cortex in this area that places this patient at higher risk for partial seizures. Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old male with GBM, admitted with episodes of left hemibody jerking and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible for this very confused and agitated individual.  The patient had multiple episodes of left hemibody shaking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized. There is some seconds in the awake record where there is a 9 hertz alpha rhythm seen on the right.  The left hemisphere demonstrates more beta as well as a breech rhythm and a phase reversal at T5.  The patient's episodes of tremulousness on the left seem to be associated  with physical discomfort or pain.  He is responsive during the events, but does not seem to recall them afterwards.
In addition, he has intermittent restlessness of the right leg which is not stereotypic in nature.
The behavioral episodes of shaking on the left are associated with muscle artifact but without a definitive EEG pattern.
Heart rate 108.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
A superimposed area of focal slowing most prominent in the left posterior temporal region.
In the sharply contoured background with a breech rhythm is suggestion of a T5 sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's motor behaviors were not associated with a well defined EEG change aside from the muscle artifact.  There is perhaps an area noted with one of the behavioral spells with perhaps a CZC4 spike but the vast majority of the patient's clinical seizures were not associated with a distinct EEG signature.
This EEG is most supportive of an epilepsia partialis continua phenomenon.  This is a technically challenging EEG due to the patient's physical discomfort and agitation, but consideration for a CZC4 epileptiform focus is appropriate. Compared to previous EEGs, the T5 focal slowing has been previously described.  Previous sharp waves have been noted from either hemisphere.  The seizure type described today seems to be a new seizure for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old male with chronic kidney disease, lupus, admitted in respiratory failure with atrial fibrillation now with intermittent jerking activity.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, fentanyl.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was a technical difficult bedside record in a critically ill patient who was receiving treatments during the EEG and awaiting dialysis.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow but continuous and lacks the typical hallmarks of either an awake or asleep individual in this obtunded patient.  There is primarily rhythmic theta with some arrhythmic delta.  Although this is a technically challenging record with perhaps some attenuation in the electrodes in the right temporal region, there is an occasional right occipital temporal sharp wave noted in the background.  No clinical jerking of the extremities is seen with the jerking.  Finally, predominant triphasic waves were noted as was shifting slowing in this overall slow record.  Intermittent attenuations were noted.
Towards the close of the record, intermittent jerking was noted.  On some occasions this was associated with movement artifact, on other occasions attenuation and on other occasions the jerkiness is associated with an overall attenuation of the background.
Heart rate:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with primarily a theta frequency background.
Shifting slowing.
Triphasic waves.
A right occipital sharp wave.
Intermittent attenuation of the background which was sometimes associated with jerking of the body or limbs.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptic seizures were identified.  Overall, the pattern described above is one more commonly seen in the context of metabolic encephalopathy as described above.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  58-year-old man with bifrontal bur holes and evacuation of subdural hematomas with change in mental status, with the wife noting that he is lip smacking and staring but never returned to baseline.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Vimpat.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software as well as patient notes and nurse's notes and patient alarms were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, the recording appears to be mainly in the delta frequencies with some intermittent faster frequencies showing up periodically.  There are some stage changes noted.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen continuously at T5/P3 with a periodicity that ranges from 0.5 Hz to 2 Hz, at times becoming slightly less organized.  These are consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.
SEIZURES:  Although there were about 2-3 rhythmic runs of the PLEDs, there were 2 electrographic seizures.  One occurred at 4:15 p.m. lasting for a minute and a half.  The 2nd one occurred at 9:43 p.m.  Both of them did not appear to have any clear clinical correlate.  They were comprised of rhythmic P3-4/T5 sharp waves, evolving in frequency and amplitude and then suddenly stopping.
HEART RATE:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior temporal and parietal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs) and electrographic seizures in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals left posterior temporal and parietal seizures as well as a focus of irritability and cerebral dysfunction in that region.  This is likely related to the known lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral  dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.

MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
HISTORY:  A 28-year-old woman with recurrent black outs with an aura of left posterior headaches since the age of 13, date of most recent event unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10.20  system with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was completed.  Photic stimulation was not completed.

Head rocking artifact is noted in the occipitoparietal region, right more so than the left.

Mild slowing of the background alpha rhythm.
Excess theta.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 55-year-old woman with asthma, depression, and epilepsy as well as chronic pain, currently seizure free.
MEDICATIONS: Singulair, gabapentin 600 at bedtime, temazepam, metoprolol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, EEG is appropriately organized for age with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and clearly accentuated frontally predominant 3-4 Hz spike and wave activity. In hyperventilation, bursts were approximately 2.5 seconds in duration, frontally predominant and symmetric. Following hyperventilation, bursts were seen typically less in a second in duration. Testing was performed during the bursts and no impairment of awareness could be demonstrated. The spike and wave discharges were seen on occasion as the patient transitioned to a drowsy state with attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in beta. Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response but spike and wave discharges occurred after, not during the photic stimulation period.
Heart rate 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to frontally predominant 3-4 Hz spike and wave activity with polyspike and wave activity accentuated by hyperventilation and early drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No clinical seizures could be demonstrated in this EEG. All bursts were brief. These findings are identical to a previous EEG 05/04/2007.

There is shifting arrhythmic delta in the temporal regions with somewhat rhythmic TIRDA noted from the left or right temporal region with a bit more arrhythmic slowing noted in the right temporal region.  Hyperventilation accentuates these findings.  The patient transitioned in and out of a drowsy state but sleep is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Significant electrode artifact was noted in some portions of the record.  Heart rate 72 BPM.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65 -year-old woman with 2 previous strokes, right-sided weakness.  The patient had an episode with loss of consciousness and had persistent confusion and cognitive slowing.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zocor, simvastatin, metoprolol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern. As the EEG begins, the overall pattern is diffusely slow and poorly organized.  There are bursts of high amplitude, generalized transients followed by brief attenuations. In addition, there is a subtle asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.  Stimulation of the patient enhances that asymmetry. An alpha rhythm appears on the right of approximately 8 Hz with slower activity on the left.  When the patient is unstimulated, she drifts back into a drowsy pattern. In later portions of the record, this is a lower voltage more featureless pattern.
Photic stimulation was attempted and was complicated by significant photoelectric artifact.  It serve to alert the patient but there was no definitive driving response.  Heart rate 84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing and disorganization.
Focal slowing on the left with disruption of faster frequency activity as well as more slow theta and delta.
Metabolic features with intermittent higher amplitude paroxysmal  discharges followed by attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function but one that involves both gray and white matter on the left, more significantly than the right. No epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 78-year-old woman admitted with confusion.  At baseline, she is awake and can communicate.  History of essential tremor treated with primidone, epilepsy, A flutter, vent-dependent respiratory failure, tracheostomy, and long hospital stay.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, vancomycin, imipenem, ropinirole, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a confused and poorly responsive patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is a mixture of delta and theta, but there is a suggestion of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm noted at times, right greater than left.  Shifting slowing is noted from either hemisphere with arrhythmic delta.  There is variability in the record with some sections of the record with more theta and other with more delta.  Tactile stimulation of the patient produces a small increase in theta activity but only briefly.
Heart rate irregular, 126 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized background slowing and disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are identified.  These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in a toxic or metabolic or other disturbance.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of body shaking.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 48-year-old woman with episodes of whole body shaking lasting half an hour to 2 hours for 1 year with no loss of consciousness or falls with bipolar anxiety, depression, and panic attacks.
MEDICATIONS:  Trazodone, Depakote, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep, stage 1, stage 2.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced abnormal discharges.
Heart Rate:  66.
Abnormal Discharges:  Focal slow waves seen rarely at T4.  One of them sharply contoured at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right midtemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right midtemporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old male with stroke, cardiac disease, status post valve repair, evaluate for refractory epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Tegretol, Keppra, carvedilol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  There were some electrode artifacts noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm but there are other sections of the record when the patient is awake when the alpha is a little slower, 8-8.5 Hz.  In wakefulness and a little bit more prominently as the patient becomes drowsy, there was focal slowing noted in the left mid temporal region.  In addition, there are also some eye artifacts which are also asymmetric, a little bit more so on the left.  As the patient drifts in and out of sleep, sharp waves emerge, some of which have an unusual field of spread.  Most seem to be in the left midtemporal or left frontal region but with a field involving the right and then there are a handful of rare right midtemporal sharp waves noted as well.  Overall, the epileptiform activity is quite subtle.  There are a handful of vertex waves noted in sleep which phase reverse to the right of midline or the left.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was transitioning into stage II sleep and did not significantly activate the record.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Focal slowing emerging as the patient becomes drowsy, despite the artifacts described above.
Sharp waves noted in drowsiness with unusual fields of spread, typically left frontal or right anterior temporal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Additional EEG monitoring may be helpful to more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old male with glioblastoma multiforme, recently evaluated last month for epilepsia partialis continua, globally aphasic with right occipital mass and left temporal mass.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Dilantin, Keppra, and morphine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient has multiple episodes of tremulousness or jerking, more so on the right hemibody than the left.  These were intermittent, and when they stopped the patient was communicative although confused and quite fragile.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is a diffusely slow, poorly organized background with apparent craniotomy on the left and high amplitude sharp waves noted on the left posterior, temporal and parietal regions.
The episodes of tremulousness that the patient experienced, which were more so on the right than the left, but with bilateral feet, and without much impairment of awareness, were associated with muscle or movement artifact.  There did not seem to be a postictal confusion, although the events were quite stereotyped in behavior.
Sharp waves from the left hemisphere and sharp waves were noted at T3, T5, P3 and O1.
When the patient was responsive, eye opening and muscle artifact were noted.
Heart rate 120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background disorganization.
Focal slowing, with more disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right today.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The seizures today represent a different seizure pattern in comparison to the seizures noted one month ago which seemed to be a pattern from CZ and C4.
The bihemispheric nature of this patient's problems may account for this phenomenon.  Overall, this is a highly epileptiform appearing EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 58-year-old gentleman with prior traumatic brain injury after a motor vehicle accident and left temporal encephalomalacia. Agitation
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, levetiracetam.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was poorly cooperative.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible in this bedside record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is 9 Hz, in maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is slightly disorganized from the right.  There is a bilateral alpha rhythm.  Rare lambda was noted in wakefulness.  In wakefulness, there is delta noted primarily in the left hemisphere, including left frontal central but with a smaller amount in the right frontal temporal region as well.  As the patient becomes drowsy, slowing of the alpha rhythm and 15 slowing was noted.  The focal slowing from the left hemisphere is most prominent in the transition in and out of sleep.
Heart rate 108 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left hemisphere with disruption of faster frequency activity and preference of somewhat rhythmic delta activity.
Background slowing and disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this individual with the history of epilepsy and acute traumatic brain injury, no epileptiform features were identified.  The focal findings may be part of this patient's previous CNS pathology.  The diffuse background slowing may be due to the acute issues or a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 20-year-old female with history of seizures described as generalized tonic-clonic with loss of consciousness for a few minutes.  Last seizures occurred 2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  During wakefulness, there were 2 bursts of generalized spike and wave, and polyspike discharges seen occurrent with a frequency of 3.5 Hz, which were frontally predominant.  These occurred in bursts lasting for 1-2 seconds.  There was no clinical seizure correlated during these bursts.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response without any photoparoxysmal response.  Hyperventilation was performed and results in symmetric slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage II sleep due to generalized spike and wave and polyspike discharges seen during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are consistent with idiopathic generalized epilepsy in the setting of a history of seizures.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old male admitted with 3 tonic-clonic seizures which began with shaking of the left arm and mouth and then went on to convulsive activity, followed by obtundation.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Keppra, benzodiazepines, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing began, the patient is in ICU and is very confused and moving about.  The background EEG is markedly abnormal with primarily a theta pattern, poorly organized with generous background beta.  In addition, there are sharp waves noted in the record with more than one localization including C3 and the right temporal region.  There is prominent theta noted in the background.
A burst of right temporal sharp waves and delta was noted at 2:35 but without a clear clinical correlate.  This burst continues as might be anticipated in an electrographic seizure but looking at the video the patient does not appear to be doing anything other than motion arrest.  There is no significant change in the patient's behavior after this 30-second discharge.  Additional bursts of right temporal sharp waves and spikes maximum in the anterior temporal region were noted at 2:47.  At the close of the EEG, the right temporal sharp waves are building up.  They have not yet evolved into the pattern of a seizure.  Of note, the patient has turned his head to the left but testing is not performed and it is difficult to determine if there is really a change in the patient's mental status.  The patient is confused but interactive throughout the EEG.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing and disorganization.
Prominent right anterior temporal sharp waves and spikes.
At least 1 electrographic seizure from the right temporal region.
Sharp waves noted on occasion from the left hemisphere as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual who has had recent, repetitive seizures, this is an ongoing ictal record although it does not meet the formal criteria for a status epilepticus record and the seizure that was recorded appeared to be with little clinical signs or symptoms and was brief.
Additional EEG recording was initiated on the evening of the 16th.

.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 74-year-old right-handed woman status post cardiac arrest on 03/17/2013.  No CPR at home but intubated by EMS.  Critically ill patient.  Additional history not available but plan is for hypothermic protocol.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Demerol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU, using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient had not been paralyzed.  She had not achieved the hypothermic goal or hyperthermia had not been started at the time of the record at 16:05.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG demonstrates a burst suppression pattern with approximately 2 bursts every 20 seconds.  The bursts are 1 to 3 seconds in duration, and are associated with a little bit of jerking and oral facial movements.  In addition, in the period of time when the EEG is suppressed, following the bursts there is a very slow oral movement and then eye flicker, a bit of jerking, and oral bursts, and then the mouth opening and closing one more time while the EEG is suppressed.  Tactile stimulation does not activate the record.
The bursts of activity are high amplitude, almost with a 4Hz spike and wave-like burst and then a suppressed background.
Heart rate difficult to discern at times due to the background artifact, but 96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a burst suppression pattern.
Postanoxic myoclonus with the bursts with oral facial movements.
Absence of reactivity or significant variability.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These are worrisome findings, more than 6 hours status post anoxic insult.  Due to this patient's cardiac condition, hypothermia protocol was initiated and additional EEG will follow.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old woman with a 17 year history of epilepsy, 3-4 tonic clonic seizures per year, last in January 2013, and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Tegretol, and phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized with an alpha rhythm of about 6-7 Hz in a pattern more of diffuse theta.  This background is intermittently disrupted by bursts of higher amplitude slowing, which are bilateral, but are more prominent on the left compared to the right.  In a disorganized pattern there is an underlying sharp wave which may be in the left mid to anterior temporal region.  In addition, as the patient transitions into stage 1 sleep with vertex waves, some of these waves forms are also noted.  In stage 1 sleep there appears to be a left posterior temporal sharp wave noted.
In the transition between wakefulness and sleep, there is intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm on either side.
Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background with hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  In addition, it does seem to elicit some asynchronous slowing and there is a question of a frontal spike and slow wave complex, left greater than right, noted in hyperventilation.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Disorganization.
Bursts of paroxysmal higher amplitude slowing, which seemed to be maximum on the left and appear to have a poorly defined underlying left mid anterior temporal sharp wave.
Rare right posterior temporal sharp waves noted in sleep.
Rare left and frontal spike and slow wave complexes in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process, but one which may involve the left hemisphere more significantly than the right.  The epileptiform activity has a preponderance in the left hemisphere.  No seizures were recorded.  If additional information is needed, an inpatient EEG monitoring session may be necessary.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change of mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old man with history of seizures, skull defect on the right, status post subdural evacuation, presents for a lung biopsy, found to have cancer.  Since biopsy has change of mental status and is agitated now with left hypodensity.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, nifedipine, aspirin, pravastatin, Flomax, gabapentin, Lovenox, calcitonin, Miralax.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during lethargy and confusion.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no longer posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  The patient appears to be awake and no clear sleep architecture is seen.  There is variability and reactivity to the EEG.  No activating procedures were performed.
Abnormal Discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen over the right hemisphere mainly at T4 and at T6, independently at P4 and O2.
Focal slow waves seen over the right hemisphere, maximal at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 40-60 microvolts.  This is associated with increased asymmetric amplitude and beta over that region consistent with a breach rhythm.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and continuously throughout the recording.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to frequent right posterior quadrant sharp waves and breach as well as focal slowing in that region in the setting of generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the right posterior quadrant region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability in that region, which is consistent with the known previous lesion and surgery in that region.  No seizures were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with a 17-year history of epilepsy with several tonic-clonic seizures per year.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Tegretol, and phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures the patient during wakefulness and stage 1 sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was about 6-7 Hz in frequency.  There was disorganized and diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  The background activity was intermittently disrupted by burst of higher amplitude bilateral delta activity most pronounced on the left side.  There were also rare left frontotemporal spike and slow wave complexes noted during hyperventilation with no evolution.  A stage 1 sleep was characterized by the presence of transient sharp waves and posts.  Hyperventilation was performed and characterized by high amplitude rhythmic delta activities.  Photic stimulation was performed and results in no driving response.  Heart rate was 60 to 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and generalized background activity.
Burst of paroxysmal high amplitude and at times sharply contoured delta waves, most pronounced on the left side.
Rare left frontotemporal spike and slow wave complexes during hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing of the background is suggestive of toxic, metabolic, infectious, or degenerative encephalopathy or due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  The presence of rare sharp waves from the right frontotemporal region is suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity of that region.  No seizures were captured.  An inpatient EEG monitoring session is recommended for further seizure evaluation.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 69-year-old male with TBSA burns to bilateral lower extremities, status post escharotomy.  He has a past history of epilepsy or seizure disorder.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, phenytoin, Percocet, heparin, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Despite the challenges of the ICU, impedances were okay.  The technologist did need to readjust some of the electrodes.  The patient was described as awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern.  At times there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  At other times, there are bursts of more rhythmic slowing identified bilaterally.  The bursts of rhythmic delta are a bit more prominent on the right than the left.  They are also a bit more prominent in the right posterior quadrant.
Heart rate:  130 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to disruption of normal background with bursts of rhythmic delta right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures, sharp waves, or spikes were noted.  The bursts of rhythmic slowing are a bit more prominent on the right than the left.  These findings may be correlated with this patient's history and imaging.  To more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy, a repeat study when the patient is out of the ICU is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29-year-old lady with history of complex partial epilepsy described as staring and sometimes walking aimlessly without her knowledge.  This is usually preceded by an aura of kind of feeling funny.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, valproic acid.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The EEG was recorded during awake and stage I sleep. Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 10 Hz frequency and 30-50 microvolts in amplitude which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is frequent focal slowing seen at F7-T3 with 2-4 Hz frequency and 20-40 microvolts amplitude.  There area frequent F7-T3 sharp waves seen with some having large spread to F3.  Seen in both wakefulness and sleep.  There are independent F8-T4 sharp waves seen mostly in sleep.  There is also independent focal slowing seen at F8-T4.  Stage I sleep was achieved which was characterized by vertex waves.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Frequent F7-T3 sharp waves seen in awake and asleep recording.
Rare F8-T4 sharp waves seen mostly in sleep.
Frequent focal slowing at F7-T3.
Independent occasional right focal slowing at F8-T4.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG because of frequent left anterior temporal sharp waves, and rare right anterior temporal sharp waves.  Also seen is frequent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region and rarely in the right anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with localization related epilepsy with seizures arising from left anterior temporal region greater than the right anterior temporal region.  This indicates focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability in bilateral anterior temporal regions independently with high epileptogenic potential.

REFERRING FOR STUDY:  Recurrent seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old woman with a history of seizures since she was 18 months of age that presents with multiple seizure types refractory to multiple medications.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Gabapentin, Depakote, Elavil, and Ritalin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, however, at times has super harmonic of 18 Hz.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.  During stage I sleep there were prominent posts seen rhythmically.  There is a generous amount of frontocentral beta seen throughout the recording.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation which produced normal discharges, however, hyperventilation accentuated focal slowing as described in abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.  At times these were very sharply contoured with a wicket-like appearance and this focal slowing was also accentuated by hyperventilation.
Focal slow waves seen independently at F8/T4 and a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen occasionally.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to frequent left anterior temporal and occasional right anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region and independently in the right anterior temporal region, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No clear seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The diffuse amount of beta may be due at least in part to medication affect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old man with sudden onset slurred speech, foaming at the mouth with unresponsiveness.  He was confused for 30 minutes after the event.
Past Medical History:  Hypertension, diabetes, old right MCA, CVA with left-sided weakness, ACOM aneurysm clipping.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, insulin, Protonix, aspirin, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, he has background rhythm of about 8.3 Hz in the bilateral occipital regions, which was reactive to eye opening.  There is right frontocentral slowing with disruption of faster frequencies on the right side.  There are occasional simple sharp waves in the right temporal region.  Drowsiness was characterized by generalized slowing.  Asymmetric vertex waves were noted.
Hyperventilation was not performed.
Photic stimulation elicited driving response at intermediate frequencies.
There was a breach rhythm noted.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is abnormal due to the presence of
Right focal slowing.
Right temporal sharp waves.
Breach rhythm, asymmetric vertex waves.
Clinical Correlation:  This EEG is suggestive of epileptogenic structural abnormality in the right hemisphere, which is consistent with the history of old stroke and aneurysm clipping.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 34-year-old female, who presents with a history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures for many years.  This is a followup EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-8 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is 6-7 Hz excess theta activity during wakefulness.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts. Stage 2 sleep is characterized by presence of k- complexes and sleep spindles. There are occasional bursts of right temporal and central slowing, most pronounced in mid temporal region at T3 during wakefulness and sleep mixed with sharply contoured delta waves lasting for 1-3 seconds with no evolution.  During wakefulness and sleep, there are occasional bursts of generalized spike and wave discharges seen appearing with a frequency of 2.5-3 Hz, which were frontally predominant.  These occurred in bursts lasting from 1-3 seconds.  There was no clinical seizure correlate during these bursts.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response without any photoparoxysmal response.  Hyperventilation was performed and resulted in diffuse slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 72 beats per minutes.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep, due to:
Generalized spike and slow wave discharges seen during wakefulness and sleep with a frequency of 2.5-3 Hz with no evolution.
Disorganized background
Excess theta activity during wakefulness and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Right central and mid temporal slowing mixed with sharply contoured wave discharges.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and excess theta activity are consistent with encephalopathy, which could be due to toxic, metabolic, infectious, medication induced, degenerative, postictal, or bilateral cerebral dysfunction. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant generalized spike and slow wave discharges and right central and temporal slowing and sharply contoured delta waves are consistent with underlying epileptogenicity with multiple foci. The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturate, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism. Clinical correlation and repeat EEG or prolonged EEG monitoring for further evolution is recommended.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 53-year-old woman with a history of seizures for 17 years presents for classification of seizures to the EMU.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproic acid, phenobarbital, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient also recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  Overall, there is a disorganized theta pattern that at times has intermixed bursts of diffuse delta that appears to be related to some drowsiness, although not always.  These bursts occur frequently and can last for seconds and be at times more prolonged up to 30 seconds.  Some of these bursts have intermixed waveforms that appear to have maximally sharp contour, sometimes in the central and sometimes in the frontal regions, although not clearly epileptiform.  Overall, they are maximally bifrontally.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Burst of generalized slowing as described above.
Generalized slow background.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to generalized slowing and burst of delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific as to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform activity was seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 63-year-old woman with a left MCA stroke, seizures, atrial fibrillation, COPD, gout, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, diabetes, history of CHF, DVT and PE, asthma, with epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Dilaudid, levetiracetam.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that can best seen over the right hemisphere that reaches 9 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some normal frontal central beta seen.
Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen occasionally at F7/T3 while awake.
Focal slowing seen continuously over F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Focal slow waves seen rarely at T4 at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Heart rate:  90.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal sharp waves and focal slowing as well as independent right mid temporal sharp waves and focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy likely arising from the left anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region consistent with a known stroke.  Lastly, there is evidence of nonspecific cerebral dysfunction over the right mid temporal region.  No seizures were seen.
