CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old woman with a history of seizures.  She has been seizure-free since August 2012.  Over the past 3 weeks the patient has been having issues with depth perception, stumbling backward, falls, vertigo and slurred speech.  A pacemaker was inserted in 2003.
MEDICATIONS:  Her medications include Dilantin, Topamax, Neurontin, morphine, atenolol, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and single EKG lead. Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation  was performed
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During maximal wakefulness the posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8.5 Hz, alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  The anterior to posterior frequency gradient is weak.  Additionally, polymorphic theta activity is captured.  Drowsiness is characterized by the attenuation of the posterior dominant rhythm and bursts of theta and delta activity.  Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the bitemporal regions, left greater than right.  This activity is independent from each other.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Independent left greater than right, mild to moderate focal temporal slowing.
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 21 minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, intermittent bitemporal mild to moderate focal slowing, left greater than right.  Diffuse cerebral slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction.   Focal bitemporal slowing is suggestive of underlying focal cerebral dysfunction, possible structural in etiology.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, the patient's sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  20 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 60-year-old woman who had a cardiac catheterization on 05/08/2013 during which she had loss of vision in both eyes.  She was subsequently found to have a cerebral artery occlusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Ultram, Zocor, Procardia, Aldactone, Namenda.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low amplitude 11 Hz activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with gaster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex wave and sleep spindles are captured.  Intermittent polymorphic theta activity is captured over the right temporal regions.  A brief run of simple intermittent rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA) is observed over the left temporal region.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate of fewer than 60 beats a minute.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent mild bitemporal slowing.
Single run of left TIRDA.
Brief stage II sleep.
Sinus bradycardia with heart rate fewer than 50 beats a minute.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and briefly asleep 20-minute EEG due to occasional mild bitemporal slowing as well as a short run of left temporal rhythmic delta activity.  Bitemporal slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  Focal rhythmic left temporal slow activity probably indicates focal left temporal cerebral dysfunction, and if clinical suspicion for seizures persists, this pattern could indicate a potential epileptogenic focus emanating from the left temporal region.  No electrographic seizures were observed.  Sinus bradycardia is noted on single EKG lead. Excess beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 57-year-old woman who was injured in a house fire May 17th.  The patient has had spells with either posturing or myoclonus.  Previous history of left craniotomy for subdural hematoma, on seizures medications, multiple sclerosis, and blindness.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Keppra, fentanyl, magnesium, and many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with a mixture of delta and theta.  There is an overlying asymmetry with a breach rhythm on the left, congruent with the patient's past history of subdural hematoma and craniotomy.  Rare left temporal sharp waves were noted.
Heart rate 108 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting slowing.
Occasional asymmetry with greater delta on the left.
Rare simple left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  The sharp waves were in the region of the patient's craniotomy.  This patient's medications and critical illness as well
as her past neurological history may all contribute to the pattern described above.  No seizures were recorded.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 38-year-old woman with history of seizure and memory loss having auras and staring, having the last one a week ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  Hyperventilation accentuated the left anterior temporal focal slowing, which I will describe in abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  Focal slow waves seen at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV intermittently throughout the recording.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 52-year-old right-handed female with history of childhood epilepsy whose last seizure was at age 17 with a past medical history of congenital hydrocephalus with right hemispheric shunt, status post craniotomy on the right side.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbatrol and gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness and drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior rhythm was slow in 7.5-8 Hz in frequency and 40-45 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates somehow with eye opening.  There was diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness most pronounced on the right side, 5-6 Hz in frequency.  Drowsiness was characterized by slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm, absence of motion and eye blink artifact.  There was breach rhythm seen in the right cerebral hemisphere most pronounced in the right posterior quadrant at times with occasional sharply contoured features.  There were frequent bursts of polymorphic theta and delta activity seen at bifrontal region most pronounced in superior frontal areas at F3 and F4 lasting 1-2 seconds.  There were also occasional sharp waves seen arising from the right temporal regions at T4/T6 during wakefulness without evolution.  There were rare epileptiform discharges arising from left posterior quadrant with no evolution. Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and resulted in no driving response.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Generalized slowing of background activity and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm during wakefulness, most pronounced on the right side.
Breach rhythm in the right posterior quadrant region.
Intermittent polymorphic delta and theta activity at times with sharply contoured features in frontotemporal regions bilaterally.
Occasional sharp waves seen arising from the right temporal region and rarely from left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Generalized slowing of the background activity and posterior rhythm (most pronounced in the right cerebral hemisphere) during wakefulness could be due to toxic, metabolic, or infectious encephalopathy.  It could also be due to sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction with structural lesion in the right cerebral hemisphere.  Breach rhythm is consistent with patient's history of craniotomy.  Occasional polymorphic theta and delta activity seen in bifrontal region and right posterior quadrant are suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the subcortical white matter in this regions.  The sharp waves seen arising from the right temporal region and rarely in left posterior quadrant region are suggestive of epileptogenicity of the temporal region in these areas. Clinical correlation is recommended.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 53-year-old woman with past medical history for 17 years, with last seizures in May and June, with associated generalized convulsion and urinary incontinence.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote and phenobarbital.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During maximal wakefulness, the background consists of somewhat monomorphic moderate amplitude 8 Hz theta activity admixed with polymorphic delta activity.  During periods of quiescence, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), bursts of delta, and periods of possible brief slow-wave sleep are captured.  Frequent bursts of variable lengths of polymorphic sharply contoured theta and delta activity are captured.  This slowing is multifocal, but most pronounced over the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and does not result in additional abnormalities.  Step photic stimulation does not result in significant change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate diffuse slowing and disorganization.
Bursts of multifocal slowing, often sharply contoured, most pronounced over the left temporal region.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21-minute awake and asleep electroencephalogram due to mild to moderate diffuse slowing and disorganization and multifocal bursts of sharply contoured slowing, most pronounced over the left temporal region.  Diffuse slowing and disorganization indicates etiologically a nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  No clear epileptiform discharges were identified.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old woman who presents with follow up for catamenial epilepsy, status post right temporal lobectomy, now seizure free.  Complains of headaches for the past 1 to 2 months, right frontal, as well as some forgetfulness with only a severe headache once.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbamazepine and levetiracetam.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta which is slightly higher in amplitude and frequency over the right frontotemporal hemisphere.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Single focal sharp waves seen over C4/F4 in wakefulness.
Focal slow waves at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously with increased amplitude over the left hemisphere consistent with a breached rhythm.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  60.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to single right frontocentral sharp wave in addition to right mid temporal continuous focal slowing and breach.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from the right central frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral structural dysfunction in the right midtemporal region, which is consistent with a known temporal lobectomy.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that this EEG is similar to ones performed on April 5, 2012 as well as the one performed on October 22, 2012 with the exception that the sharp waves seen today appear to be more central frontal rather than temporal.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  This was seen best over the left hemisphere. ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen almost continuously over the right hemisphere, maximal at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz, and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Focal slow waves seen occasionally at T3 and independently at C3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  At times, there were sharply contoured.
Heart rate 60.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right continuous mid temporal slowing in addition to occasional left mid temporal and central slowing.

In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal and central region, all of which are likely related to the known strokes. CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 60-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy, some seizures begin with tingling in her nose or distal paresthesias.  Other more significant seizures with tonic-clonic activity.  Onset in 2003.  Previous EEG monitoring for nasal tingling and distal paresthesias.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, phenytoin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Impedances were acceptable aside from T1 and T2.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
There are a handful of subtle, underlying abnormalities.  These include a rare, discrete right temporal sharp wave with unusual field of spread, but when reviewed with an average reference, it is maximal on the right with a field involving the left (transverse dipole?) .  In addition, there is a suggestion of low voltage fast activity noted on the left.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Discrete right temporal sharp waves with an unusual field of spread.
Subtle, fast activity or a low voltage spike in the left frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to this patient's previous EEGs spanning 2003 to the present, both of these findings have been identified in the past.  The left frontal activity was noted during the patient's long-term video EEG monitoring, and the right temporal findings, although rare for this patient, have been noted since 2003.
